comment.narrative:
Baseline 1:
1.1.	Uzbekistan is in compliance with 2015-2017 Montreal Protocol (MP) mandated HCFC reduction targets and implements MSP GEF programme to meet final milestones by 2020 and 2030 respectively

Baseline 2:
2.1.	No survey of ODS alternatives use in Uzbekistan previously conducted;
2.2.	No systematic data on ODS alternatives use in Uzbekistan to enable accurate decision-making;
2.3.	Current legislation, i.e. Law on Atmosphere Air Protection, is outdated (because a number of years passed from its adoption) and may hinder the completion of the accelerated HCFC phase-out;
2.4.	Central Customs Laboratory of the State Customs Committee has outdated refrigerant standards for calibrating their gas chromatographs to ensure accurate measurement of HCFC substances during import/export/transit operations which inhibits enforcement action on illegal trade; 
2.5.	Limited knowledge on the side of environmental inspectors and importers of HCFCs about the newly introduced national system of ODS/ODS alternatives import/export electronic declaration which limits the effective operation of the system;
2.6.	The limited capacity of the State Customs Committee on storage of seized smuggled ODS/ODS alternatives resulting in ineffective management of seized ODS;
2.7.	Participation in regional UN Environment supported CAP network meetings and conferences are constrained by limited in-house resources which impedes information exchange on modern HCFC control procedures.

Baseline 3:
3.1.	Current coverage of the HCFC re-use system is limited and requires an extension to the national level; limited basic servicing tools to strengthening HCFC re-use;
3.2.	Lack of special servicing equipment for zero-ODS and low GWP technologies to support the transition from HCFC-based technologies to non-HCFC based ones;
3.3.	Very limited experience (knowledge and skills) at technician level on assembly, installation, operation and maintenance of commercial/industrial zero-ODS and low-GWP alternative t

Target 1
Target 1.2.1
A) With the support of the project, the resolution of the Cabinet of Ministers of the Republic of Uzbekistan (#126 dd 9.03.2021) on “National program on Complete ODS phase-out” and its roadmap were adopted. The following project proposals were accepted by the Government:
1. Establishment of National Refrigeration and Air Conditioning (RAC) Association- since there have been several unsuccessful attempts to register association during past 10 years, the project starts with inclusion of a feasibility study of establishing the RAC Association to demonstrate its advantages in coordination the industry.
2. Review of socio-economic impacts of the Kigali Amendment ratification - completed by the project and submitted to the State Committee for Ecology for further consideration and elaboration.
3. Regular capacity development of customs and enforcement officers on more efficient control of HCFCs and their alternatives during import/export activities.
4. Technology transition from Ozone depleting substances (ODS) based to ozone-friendly and low-GWP technologies:
- Strengthening the HCFC (ODS) re-use system across the country to support industry in not exceeding the servicing tail in the RAC sector till 2030;
- Implementation of demonstration projects on HCFC replacement with ODS-free/low GWP alternatives for further replication countrywide;
- Establishing RAC training centers to support in obtaining/advancing skills on use of new technologies;
- Establishing a database on use of ODS and products containing them based on project developed system www.report.o3.uz
5. Gender mainstreaming in the RAC sector of Uzbekistan
- Attracting women to the RAC sector through education, development of new business skills.
- Support inclusiveness by promoting gender aspects /mainstreaming in the RAC sector.
6. Public awareness raising on protection of the Ozone Layer:
- Information exchange within the industries and awareness raising among stakeholders and population.
- Awareness raising campaigns devoted to the celebration of World Ozone Day
B) The following changes to the national legislation are proposed in case of ratification of the Kigali Amendment:
1. Introducing a “regulated substances” term to the national legislation in respect to HFCs;
2. Introducing a ban for production of regulated substances in national legislation;
In addition, the provisional application of Kigali Amendment control measures proposed to implement until the ratification of the amendment.

Target 1.2.2 Review and analysis of national legislation on refrigeration and air conditioning equipment disposal including equipment containing ODS is conducted. Based on the international best practices, recommendations for update of the national legislation are developed. The report will be shared with the State Committee for Ecology and Environmental Protection for consideration.

Target 1.3.4 
- Laptop and spare parts for printers provided to the State Customs Committee for better control over HCFC movement and phase-out.
- In addition, as per the decision of the 5th Project Board virtual meeting and RTA approval, two laptops were provided to the State Committee for Ecology and Environment Protection for better control over HCFC movement and phase-out. 

Target 1.3.5
- Experience sharing of Uzbekistan on HPMP programme and HCFC re-use system is conducted within EU4CLIMATE workshop (virtually) in April 2021;
- Project shared Uzbekistan experience on gender mainstreaming to RAC sector at Webinar on Montreal Protocol and Gender organized by UNDP HQ in May 2021;
- State Committee for Ecology and Environmental Protection, State Customs Committee and project participated in discussion on ban of disposable cylinders at online workshop of the Montreal Protocol Europe and Central Asia Network under UNEP OzonAction program in November, 2021

Target 2
Target 2.1.1
- Project established six (6) new (4 recycling and 2 reclaim) and upgraded six (6) operating (5 recycling and 1 reclaim) centers throughout the all geographic regions of the country to ensure a nation wide HCFC re-use system and its effective operation;
- 24 technicians (2 women) trained and their skills upgraded during workshop for Reclaim and Recycle centers technicians in Fergana city (eastern part of the country) in March 2021;
- Equipment and tools for these centers were procured and handed over into technicians hands to improve their daily operations;

Target 2.1.2
- 2,101 kg of HCFCs have been recycled and 268 kg of HCFCs have been reclaimed based on collected data via report.o3.uz - this helps in further capacity strengthening for the national HCFC re-use system that will allow to dramatically reduce HCFC importations in line with Uzbekistans obligations under the Montreal Protocol. 

Target 2.1.4 
Necessary consumables for public and private enterprises in the RAC sector were procured and handed over into technicians hands by the end of 2021 to improve their daily operations;

Target 2.2.1 
- Demonstration project with LLC “Khiva Maishiy Texnika” on “Replacement of small-scale production commercial refrigeration line using HCFCs to zero-ODS and low-GWP technology on natural refrigerants – propane (R290) and/or isobutane (R600a)” has been launched;
- Partnership agreement on the demonstration project with “Albatros Service” Family Enterprise (Fergana, Fergana region) on “Replacement of small-scale production commercial refrigeration line using HCFCs to zero-ODS and low-GWP technology on natural refrigerants – propane (R290) and/or isobutane (R600a)” has been developed and implemented. Procurement of equipment and tools for demonstration project with “Albatros Service” FE is expected to be delivered by the end of 2021;
- Implementation of the demonstration project with Jizzah branch of the Republican Research Center for Emergency Medicine on replacement of HCFC-based air-conditioning system with ozone-friendly, low GWP and energy-efficient technology has been resumed. The estimate project cost is over USD 1 million with contribution of the project in the amount of USD 210,000. Jizzakh regional local government allocated about 1 billion UZS for fan-coil units and to transfer USD 50,000 (roughly USD 50,000) to UNDP Uzbekistan for procurement of chillers.
- Contribution of the parties document for the demonstration project with Bek Adolat Temir LLC for replacement of refrigerators using HCFCs with energy-efficient and ozone-friendly technologies with low GWP is agreed 

Target 2.2.4 
- 167 technicians (47% women) trained through the launched web-site (www.e-learning.o3.uz) and skills are upgraded on best practices in refrigeration (RAC), including ozone-friendly and energy efficient technology with low GWP. 

Target 3
Target 3.1.1 
-9 banners in Uzbek language were developed and printed for RAC training centers at “Monomarkaz” (Monocenter) vocational training centers under Ministry of Employment and Labor Relations of the Republic of Uzbekistan as an information source on RAC technologies including ozone-friendly ones;
- 121 posts, aimed at enhancing the visualization of ozone protection activities in Uzbekistan, published in social and mass-media channels, central website of UNDP Uzbekistan and partner organizations’ online platforms;
- An online interactive map (www.i-map.o3.uz) was developed to have a visual picture of project implementation throughout Uzbekistan, which makes it easier to share/discuss projects components and associated implementation progress with Project Boards members and other stakeholders;
- Video lessons (8 parts) on installation, servicing and maintenance of split air-conditioners and refrigerators in three languages (Uzbek, Russian and Karakalpak) launched at www.e-learning.o3.uz 

Target 3.1.2 
- Media promotion of animation clips “Ozonjon’s story” and “Lesson on ozone layer” were supported at national TV channels “Oilaviy”, “Aqlvoy” and “Bolajon” on World Environment Day;
- 1 TV studio live interview and success story of woman-technician were promoted at Oilaviy TV channel on the Earth Day;
- Workshop and master-class on HCFC re-use equipment for HCFC re-use centers in Fergana city (eastern Uzbekistan) were organized in May 2021.
- World Ozone Day compaign was conducted:
   - in 1984 schools of the country held awareness lessons on protection of the ozone layer: 57409 schoolchildren participated (51% are schoolgirls);
   - Equipment for servicing refrigeration and air-conditioning equipment was handed over to the winners of the startup contest for attracting women to RAC sector;
   - An online contest was held to improve knowledge through the www.e-learning.o3.uz platform in two categories (woman- and man-technicians);
   - A master class was held by a woman technician for the winners of the startup contest

Target 3.2.3 
- A comprehensive resource mobilization strategy for RAC sector has been developed by the project with a potential list of donors regionally and globally based which can support a low-carbon technological transition in Uzbekistan.
- Meeting with representatives UNDP/RUSAID supported project on advantages of applications of zero-ODP, low-GWP and efficient refrigeration technologies in coldrooms (agribusiness) is conducted and relevant cost estimates provided for consideration in implementation of their projects.
- Due to high capital costs of these technologies (for example, in case of coldrooms, they could be three times more expensive than the high GWP HFC-based technology), the end-users prefer to use available cheaper technologies on HFCs. 

